 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 2020<br> <font color=#333333>(10/4/02 5:56:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm46.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=65.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: ???</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> why does it have to be a complete heal<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I made a mistake.<br>
<br>
By factoring HP out of my model, leaving only DPS and seconds, then barring aggro, a nuke was always better than a heal.  If that was the case, then the only point of a heal is to save the pet from death, and the existing heals do not accomplish that.  Hence, I concluded, mistakenly, that only a near substitute for CH/mend would make a significant difference.<br>
<br>
However, a CH/mend substitute would also be much better than chaining, which would then become obsolete, which is why I proposed a strong limit on it.<br>
<br>
But the simple model is only correct for fights where the pet lives long enough to allow the spells to be cast to close the second gap.<br>
<br>
I am going back to the drawing board, and revising the model to include both mob and pet hitpoints, and not just DPS and see what the consequences are for mid-range pet heals.<br>
<br>
I can tell you this.  Improving the mana ratios on the 50+ pet heals will modestly increase the range of mobs against which sustaining pets is an option, and modestly reduce down time.  Neither will break the game, and both would certainly help those who wish to sustain pets.<br>
<br>
For me, the fire line are cheap substitutes for complete heal.  These would dramaticly increase the power of magicians, eliminate chaining as a viable alternative while conferring all the advantages of chaining to sustaining with no drawbacks, and would allow mages to solo near as well as a cleric/mage duo.  I do not think the mage class is so bad off that it needs such drastic medicine.<br>
<br>
The question remains in my mind, how good a medium heal is reasonable.<br>
<br>
